  1. Pemphigus vulgaris
  2. Pemphigus foliaceus
  3. IgA pemphigus

Vulgaris -> the V points downwards -> suprabasal bullae

Suprabasal acantholytic blisters Subcorneal acantholytic bliters subcorneal or intraepidermal acantholytic blisters
IgG antibodies against desmoglein 3 or both desmoglein 1 and desmoglein 3 Desmoglein 1 Associated with lymphoproliferative disorders:non-Hodgkin lymphoma, chronic lymphocytic leukemia, and Castleman's disease.
  • Rare, ⭐life threatening
  • ⭐Antibodies against desmosomal cadherin found between epidermal cells. -> intraepidermal blister in skin and mucous membranes -> erosions
  • ⭐Oral lesions are common (70%) - can precede skin lesions
  • ⭐Pemphigus: Painful, Intraepidermal, flaccid, fragile blisters and itchy erosions.
  • ⭐Nikolsky sign +ve <- rubbing normal skin causes sloughing.
  • ⭐Usually occurs in adulthood.
  • ⭐Recognised triggers: ACEi, rifampicin and penicillamine.
  • ⭐Can have paraneoplastic association with non-hodgkin's lymphoma or chronic lymphocytic leukemia.
  • Lateral pressure applied to the border of a blister causes displacement of the epidermis and extension of the blister.
  • There is weakening of the assoociation between corneal and granular layers because of breakdown of desmosomes.
  • Apparently normal skin between the obvious blistering lesions is also affected.

Nikolsky sign is pathognomonic for

  • Occurs over 60 years of age.
  • IgG autoantibodies that target basement membrane cell -> dermo-epidermal junction breakdown -> subepidermal split
  • Tense blisters
  • Steroid and steroid sparing drugs for treatment.
  • No scarring
  • Course: acute or insidious episodes which remit.
  • Severe pruritus.Source
  • Treatment can be stopped after few years but disease often recurs.
  • Can involve mucous membranes (20%).
  • Can be triggered by vaccination (in children) and drugs (NSAIDS, ACEi, frusemide)
  • Pemphigoid gestationalis is rare and occurs in the latter half of #pregnancy (T2 and T3) and post partum.
